07117nam a22006855i 9780773555631DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735556317 a10.1515/97807735556312doi  a(DE-B1597)657000  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPOL0700002bisacsh04aThe Criminalization of Migration :bContext and Consequences /ced. by James C. Simeon, Idil Atak. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Refugee and Forced Migration Studies ;v100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword: Protecting The Human Rights Of Migrants As Part Of A Long-Term Strategic Vision On Mobility And Diversity -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: The Criminalization of Migration: Context and Consequences -- tThe Criminalization of Migration and Its Intended and Unintended Consequences -- tThe (Mis-)Uses of Analogy: Constructing and Challenging Crimmigration in Canada -- tTreating the Symptom, Ignoring the Cause: Recent People-Smuggling Developments in Canada and Around the World -- tAnti-Trafficking and Exclusion: Reinforcing Canadian Boundaries through Human Rights Discourse -- tThe Criminalization and the Exclusion of Refugees in Canada and Abroad -- tRecent Jurisprudential Trends in the Interpretation of Complicity in Article 1F(a) Crimes -- tAn Analysis of Post-Ezokola and JS Jurisprudence on Exclusion -- tThe Interpretation of Exclusion 1F(b) of the 1951 Refugee Convention Internationally and in Canada -- tCrimmigration Responses to “Migration Crises”: Historical and Comparative Perspectives -- tAttrition through Enforcement and the Deportations of Syrians from Jordan and Turkey -- tIs the US Gaming Refugee Status for Central Americans? A Study of the Refugee Status Determination Process for Central American Women and Their Children -- tA Population Takes Flight: The Irish Famine Migration in Boston, Montreal, and Liverpool, and the Politics of Marginalization and Criminalization -- tCriminalizing Refugees and Other Forced Migrants: Current Dynamics, Future Challenges, and Prospects -- tBack to the Future: Shifts in Canadian Refugee Policy Over Four Decades -- tScoping the Range of Initiatives for Protecting the Employment and Labour Rights of Illegalized Migrants -- tin Canada and Abroad -- tProgress towards a Common European Asylum System? The Migration Crisis in Europe -- tConclusions -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith over 240 million migrants in the world, including over 65 million forced migrants and refugees, states have turned to draconian measures to stem the flow of irregular migration, including the criminalization of migration itself. Canada, perceived as a nation of immigrants and touted as one of the most generous countries in the world today for its reception of refugees, has not been immune from these practices. This book examines "crimmigration" – the criminalization of migration – from national and comparative perspectives, drawing attention to the increasing use of criminal law measures, public policies, and practices that stigmatize or diminish the rights of forced migrants and refugees within a dominant public discourse that not only stereotypes and criminalizes but marginalizes forced migrants. Leading researchers, legal scholars, and practitioners provide in-depth analyses of theoretical concerns, legal and public policy dimensions, historic migration crises, and the current dynamics and future prospects of crimmigration. The editors situate each chapter within the existing migration literature and outline a way forward for the decriminalization of migration through the vigorous promotion and advancement of human rights. Building on recent legal, policy, academic, and advocacy initiatives, The Criminalization of Migration maps how the predominant trend toward the criminalization of migration in Canada and abroad can be reversed for the benefit of all, especially those forced to migrate for the protection of their inherent human rights and dignity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEmigration and immigration lawzCanada. 0aHuman rightszCanada. 0aRefugeesxGovernment policyzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Immigration.2bisacsh1 aAtak, Idil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtak, Idil, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBauder, Harald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBen-Arieh, Galya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrépeau, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleeson, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodspeed, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Angus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHannan, Charity-Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorner, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHudson, Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaye, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeighen, Warda Shazadi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMolnar, Petra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRikhof, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimeon, James C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimeon, James C., 